ips between men and women, the manners and customs of Europeans and Middle Easterners, and the differences between contemporary European and Arabic literatures. Al-Shidyaq also celebrates the genius and beauty of the classical Arabic language.Akin to Sterne and Rabelais in his satirical outlook and technical inventiveness, al-Shidyaq produced in Leg Over Leg a work that is unique and unclassifiable. It was initially widely condemned for its attacks on authority, its religious skepticism, and its “obscenity,” and later editions were often abridged. This is the first English translation of the work and reproduces the original Arabic text, published under the author’s supervision in 1855.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aArabic languagexLexicography. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh1 aDavies, Humphrey, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081472937340uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814745243.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814745243423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814745243/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK